Pan Seared Salmon with Creamy Garlic Dijon Sauce üòã ~
Salmon with Creamy Garlic Dijon Sauce: This is such a flavorful, elegant salmon recipe that anyone can pull off. It's comes together so quickly yet it's sure to impress anyone. Pan seared salmon is perfectly delicious on it's own but when you add a bright dijon sauce like this it takes it to a whole new level!
By @cookingclassy
~
4 (6 - 7 oz) skinless salmon fillets
3 tsp olive oil
Salt and freshly ground black pepper
3 garlic cloves, minced (1 Tbsp)
1/2 tsp cornstarch
1/2 cup heavy cream
1 1/2 Tbsp dijon mustard (or a little more to taste)
1/2 tsp honey
1/2 cup low-sodium chicken broth
1 Tbsp minced fresh dill
Instructions
Heat a large non-stick skillets over medium-high heat (or use two skillets if you used large 7 - 8 oz fillets like I did so they aren't overcrowded).
Add 1 1/2 tsp olive oil to each skillet. Dab both sides of salmon dry with paper towels and season both sides with salt and pepper.
Place salmon in skillet (top of salmon turned down). Let sear until golden brown on bottom, about 4 minutes then flip and continue to cook to desired doneness, about 2 - 3 minutes longer.
Meanwhile, in a liquid measuring cup whisk together cornstarch with 1 tbsp cream, then mix in enough cream to measure 1/2 cup. Whisk in dijon mustard and honey.
Remove salmon from skillet and transfer to a plate, leaving oil in one skillet. Tent salmon with foil.
Add garlic to skillet with oil set over medium heat, saute until just barely golden brown, about 20 - 30 seconds. Pour in chicken broth.
Bring to a simmer then reduce heat to medium-low and let simmer until reduced by about 2/3, about 3 minutes.
Whisk cream mixture once more then pour into skillet. Cook and stir, bringing to a simmer. Let simmer gently, while stirring, for about 30 seconds.
Remove from heat stir in dill, return salmon fillets to pan, spoon sauce over salmon. Serve warm.

I‚Äôm calling this is a ‚Äúbuild your glutes‚Äù workout, but getting a bigger butt isn‚Äôt just doing a few certain exercises. It‚Äôs a combination of a few things.
My biggest tips for growing your glutes are:
1) EAT FOOOOOD. Don‚Äôt be afraid to fuel your body, especially if you‚Äôre training hard in the gym. If you‚Äôre not eating enough..your glutes won‚Äôt grow. Unless you‚Äôre new to lifting, you‚Äôll need to be in a slight caloric surplus to gain muscle. So carb up babe.
2) Get in your workouts. I do a combination of compound and isolation exercises. I train glutes 2-3x per week. Some might say this is too much frequency, which may be true for some people. With that said, I‚Äôve trained my booty 1-2 per week for the loooooongest time and never saw the results I wanted until I increased my frequency to 2-3x per week.
3) Push that mothahhhhh fudging weight. Don‚Äôt be afraid to lift heavy! Body weight exercises can be great, but if you want to add mass to that üçë then throw on another plate... or two... or threeeeee.üòú
4) Drink yooo watah üí¶ 
Your muscles are made up of 80% water. If you‚Äôre not drinking enough..how do you expect your body to perform at its finest? Drink up.
5) Make sure your gut is happy. Sounds weird for a booty tip lol but if your gut is inflamed it can keep you from absorbing nutrients your body needs to function properly.
6) Make sure your protein intake is high enough while you‚Äôre building muscle. I can‚Äôt tell you how many grams you should be eating because we all have different bodies. I personally eat anywhere from 80-100 grams of protein per day at 114lbs.
-

Disregarding how AWK I look in the first pic üòÇü§¶üèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è, that‚Äôs the booty I started out with! I still loved my body in that picture but I strived for new goals which was building my glutes! .
I spent the last 2 years changing my diet and workout routine! Not one single part about this journey has been easy. It‚Äôs taken hard work, consistency, sacrifice, and the want and determination to change! Sorry I don‚Äôt sugar coat things for ya, I tell it how it izzzz üíï
.
BUT anyone is capable of accomplishing what they set their minds to do! Everyone‚Äôs body responds differently to nutrition and training so that‚Äôs why it‚Äôs super important to find what works best for YOU. .
My biggest booty building advice would be, if you‚Äôre trying to grow your glutes you must EAT. If you eat a lighter diet and lift heavy, you‚Äôre not going to see the muscle mass development you want. That will simply lean out and tone your muscle (which is great if that‚Äôs what you‚Äôre going for!). .
If you eat in a caloric surplus, you must train harder in order for your body to process the extra nutrients properly instead of storing it as extra fat! If you eat more and train light, your body will store the extra food as fat. .
And lastly, I recommend training glutes 3x per week! When I only trained glutes once a week, I saw no progress. Again, this is what worked for ME, it may not work for everyone but give it a try if you find yourself at a plateau üòäüí™üèº .
